{"title":"DPF-CM: A Data Processing Framework with Privacy-Preserving Vector Databases for Chinese Medical LLMs Training and Deployment","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Open-source Chinese medical datasets are largely Q&A without explicit instructions, which weakens LLM instruction-following and generalization, especially in multi-turn dialogues.","method":"Introduce question-oriented instruction generation via chained examples. Examples are LLM-scored and ordered from low to high quality, then linked in a chain-of-thought style prompt (E1 + instruct + E2 + instruct* + ... + EN + instruct* + target question) to drive step-by-step refinement. This progressive context encourages the model to learn why later examples are better and produce higher-quality instructions, outperforming standard few-shot prompting and training without instructions (ablation Tables 10–11; method details in Sec. 3.2)."},{"problem":"Preference datasets for RLHF/DPO in the medical domain contain noisy pairs (contradictory, indistinguishable, or overly easy), which degrade training of reward models and downstream alignment.","method":"Train multiple reward models (five with different seeds) and compute a per-sample preference distance rθ(x,yc)−rθ(x,yr); average distances across models to stabilize judgments. Filter out samples whose distances are consistently negative (label contradictions) or excessively large (trivial/easy) based on thresholds, thereby denoising the preference data. This ensemble-based filtering improves performance across multi-turn/single-turn dialogues, terminology, and benchmarks (Sec. 3.3; Table 12)."},{"problem":"Chinese medical LLMs risk leaking memorized training data at deployment, threatening patient privacy.","method":"Propose PPVD, a four-step privacy-preserving vector database approach: (1) model memory search by splitting training samples into prompt/label and detecting memorization via ROUGE-L threshold; (2) build a high-risk database using intermediate embeddings of memorized samples; (3) construct a secure database by prompting a general LLM with the prompt and concatenating its response, then extracting intermediate embeddings; (4) match-and-replace at inference by cosine similarity between current intermediate embeddings and the high-risk DB, returning the secure embedding’s content when above threshold. On 100k samples, only 1.81% were highly memorized; PPVD reduced their average similarity from >0.85 to 0.58 (~0.27 drop) with minimal utility loss (Sec. 4; Tables 14–15; privacy reduction also summarized in abstract)."}]}
